etymologies: mid 16th century; earliest use found in Thomas Chaloner (1521–1565), diplomat and writer. From classical Latin dēlēbilis that may be blotted out (from dēlēre + -bilis), in some forms with remodelling after adjectives in -ible

definitions: Capable of being erased, deleted, or effaced. Frequently figurative. Often contrasted with indelible.
